segments.text: So they said, no, that would be it for the day.
So we were just getting ready to rev up our engines.
And we had our engines running the whole time.
But when you're sitting waiting or something, you turn down the RPMs.
And so we were just getting ready to rev them up and take off.
And one lone rocket was dropped into the LZ.
And it hit about .
I'd say maybe five yards from the helicopter on my side.
When it hit, the impact almost threw me over on top of the co-pilot, which sits on the left-hand side of the aircraft.
And out of instinct, he took off.
And the other, our lead man, took off.
And at the time, we didn't really know what had happened other than there was a big bang.
I sort of looked down.
At a time like that, you don't really feel that much.
I looked down and noticed my arm was bleeding, and it was bleeding quite heavily.
So I grabbed the pressure point in my upper right arm, and the bleeding stopped.
But I couldn't work my right hand.
So with my left hand, I got on the intercom.
and asked the crew how they were.
And the crew chief and the gunner down in the belly said they were OK. And then the co-pilot said he was OK. We tried to contact the other helicopter on the radio, and there was no response.
Our radios had been shot out.
We had intercom within the helicopter, but no radio contact.

copilot took off and in the meantime I was holding onto my arm trying to keep the bleeding down and we lost sight of our lead helicopter but the copilot was losing power in our helicopter and couldn't get any altitude and we got about

maybe a mile and a half or two miles out of Camp Carroll and we always called it Charlie Charlie and he started losing total control I mean we just started sloshing all over the place like a wounded duck so he set it down in an open field and so he went through the
procedures right quick, shutting down the engine, stopping the rotor blades and everything.
And we looked back, and the lead helicopter had seen us going down, so they were coming down to pick us up.
So we quite hastily got out and ran to get in the other helicopter.
And all this time, there was really no pain.
I saw blood and all that, and like I said, the crew chief and the gunner both said that they were okay.
Once we got in the other aircraft, we found out that I had been hitting the right arm and the right leg.
The crew chief had been hitting both calves, the left calf and the right calf, and the gunner had been hitting the right calf.
And didn't even know it until we got in the other airplane.
So right away they ran us, hustled us on down to Dong Ha to Delta Med and got us in the first aid down there.
And I didn't see the other two, the crew chief and the gunner, for I guess it was two days before I saw them again.

They put us aboard C-130 at Dong Ha, flew us down to Phu Bai, and got into, I don't remember what the designation of the med station was down there, but they performed surgery on me there and took out all but one piece of shrapnel, which I still have in my leg.
But it was sort of ironic, I guess.
I don't know if that's the right term or anything.
But this happened on a Monday.
I think it was, if I'm not mistaken, it was April the 13th.
It was either April the 13th or May the 13th.
And it was May the 13th.
Monday, and on Friday, I was already scheduled to meet my wife in Hawaii for R&R.
And I just, the only thing that passed through my mind when I got hit was, oh no, there goes my R&R, what am I gonna do?
I wasn't worried about dying at all.
I was just worried about missing my R&R.
So, a chaplain came through,

ward where I was in Fubi and I told him what the situation was about meeting my wife in Hawaii and all this and I asked him to contact her and let her know that I had been wounded but I was okay and that I wouldn't be able to meet her in Hawaii so he said okay he'd take care of it and

So on Tuesday, the next day, they decided that I could go ahead and be transferred back out to the ship where we were operating off of, and let the flight surgeon, and they had a tremendous medical staff on board ship too, and let them take care of me.
Got back out to the ship, and I talked to the flight surgeon.
He checked me over and checked all my stitches and everything, and he said he thought it'd be okay, if I felt like it, to go ahead and go to Hawaii.
So I said, okay, we'll go for it.
So I figured that my wife wouldn't be there, but I'd be there, and I'd call her as soon as I got there, and she could be there the next day, so we'd miss one day out of a five-day R&R.
So when I got there, I wasn't even looking for her.
But she was there because she was never contacted that I was not going to be there.
So we had a pretty good R&R.
But it was quite strange because at the time, she was living with her parents.
And this was in May.
And she had given birth to our first daughter in February.
So her daughter was three months old, and she was too young to come with her.
So it was just she and I.
And as it came to pass, I didn't see my daughter until November when I got home, and she was nine months old at the time.
I saw some pictures of her, but I didn't see my daughter until she was nine months old.
With the wound and everything, I was a little incapacitated.
I wasn't quite able to perform up to expectations.
But when there's a will, there's a way.
So we had a pretty good R&R, five days in Hawaii.
You can't argue with that.
And then after the R&R, I went back to Hawaii.
when I got back into Nam I flew into Da Nang and at the time our squadron was in the process of changing ships and so they had offloaded back into Phu Bai for about three days prior they offloaded
And then three days later, they were supposed to load back onto the other ship.
And so the flight surgeon said that it would be cleaner surroundings for me to stay in Da Nang.
So I stayed in Da Nang during all this and went back aboard ship after everything was all situated and everything.
And I was unable to fly for 89 days with my wound and wounds.
And I don't remember exactly when it was, but it was about six weeks, I guess, after the wound.
I was all set to go down and get an up chip from the flight surgeon so I could start flying again.
And I woke up in the morning, and I had a big old pus pocket on my leg where my wound was.
I went down and they lanced it and had to go in and remove another piece of shrapnel which had a little bit of flight suit on it and that's what caused the infection.
So I spent a total of 89 relatively boring days aboard ship watching movies at night and sitting in the room listening to
tapes and the like during the day.
It was quite boring, absolutely.
Ship life is boring anyway, but when you can't get out and do anything, you know, it's really terrible.
Where was this ship stationed?
It was off the coast.
I don't know how far off the coast.
I'd say probably about
20 or 25 miles in the Fu Ba Quang tree area.
It had a specific pattern that it would run, but it was quite close to the coast at all times, except I'd almost forgotten about this, but during my convalescent period, the ship
had to go back to the Philippines for some kind of repairs.
I'm not even sure what it was.
And so I stayed on board the ship.
Excuse me.
with one other officer and about six enlisted men from our squadron and went with the ship to the Philippines and had another what you might call R&R there.
We had a little bit of work to do on about three of the helicopters, which the enlisted men took care of.
And the other officer, Captain McAlka, he was a designated test pilot.
And in order for me to go, they had to designate me as a test pilot too, just to make it what you might call a legal trip.
even though it didn't do any flying.
It doesn't do much good to be a test pilot when you're grounded anyway because of wounds.
But I think we spent about seven or eight days in the Philippines, which was sort of nice, but then again, unconsequential.
You were in Vietnam during the Tet Offensive.
What did you know about it, and how did it affect you?
Well, at the time, we pretty much called it the way offensive, since we were stationed at Phu Bai at the time, which was only, oh, roughly speaking, I guess 12 to 15 miles south of Hue.
We had a little bit of an inkling about it a day or two ahead of time that something seemed to be brewing.
And of course Tet being a national holiday or a period of celebration or whatever.
I'm not sure if it's their New Year's or what, but anyway it's a time of celebration for the Vietnamese.
But there seemed to be a little more activity prior to it than in the past.
And everybody was sort of warned to, well, I wouldn't say warned, but informed to keep your eye out.
And before we knew it, the way had been overtaken.
I mean, just slam and it was done.
It didn't affect us, even being as close as we were, it didn't affect us too terribly much as far as security was concerned.
It stepped up our activity quite a bit as far as CNC missions, medevac, and the like.
We would take some incoming rockets and mortars at night.
It's amazing how fast you can get out of a hooch and into a bunker when you need to.
You can almost hear the mortars leaving the tubes in your sleep, so you're halfway there before you wake up.
We didn't have any casualties from incoming.
You weren't on the ship at this time?
No, we were in Fubai.
Because this was in, I can't remember exactly what the dates are for Tet, but it's January or February or something like that.
We didn't go aboard ship until March, I believe it was.
So we were in Fubai at the time.
And we had
like I say, some CNC missions in the way and some medevac.
It was really sort of funny in a way, but then again quite dangerous.
One day we were going in for a medevac and we got a call in and they told us the approximate coordinates for the LZ in the city of Way.

it was always a common practice of course the grunts didn't hold up to it very well but if you didn't know exactly where the LZ was the helicopter would ask the radio controller on the ground he would say pop a smoke pop a smoke grenade and the guy on the ground was supposed to pop a smoke grenade and then
the helicopter pilot would confirm the color of the smoke.
Well, this radio operator on the ground, we said, pop a smoke.
And he said, Roger, pop in a yellow smoke.
And he threw out a yellow smoke grenade.
And there were five yellow smoke grenades thrown out in the city of Hue.
So, you know, that's why the practice is to throw out the smoke and then you ask what color it is or whatever instead of saying what color you're going to pop.
It's which of those five are you going to land at?
And it was quite scary, you know.
Some of these guys on the ground, if they don't know what the procedure is, could really wipe somebody out.
What did they end up doing?
Well, we asked him to pop another smoke and not say what color it was.
No, we didn't ask him to.
We just flat told him to.
And we took a little fire on the way in, but, you know, from the surrounding area, but we made a safe in and out trip.
You mentioned that y'all called it the Huey Offensive.
You weren't familiar with the Tet Offensive that
that was a day before the Hue Offensive that happened in Saigon.
Were you all familiar with it at the time?
At my position in the rank and file, no.
I would imagine possibly that our squadron commander knew about it or whatever.
The ordinary pilots and the ones who were not involved in intelligence and the like didn't really have any knowledge of it until afterwards.
The way was right there, and that's all we were concerned about.
Did you observe any kind of changes after the Huey offensive in strategy, military strategy?
or what not?
The whole pace of the war seemed, war, conflict seemed to pick up.
And it's sort of hard for me to say since I was not directly involved with anything in
S2, which is intelligence.
It's hard to say actually what changes there might have been because, like I say, in March we went aboard ship, which changed our whole strategy and tactics anyway.
But then again,
There was a whole lot more activity.
The Army was brought into that northern area.
Khe Sanh fell.
We were quite involved with Khe Sanh.
We would have C&C and medevac patrols up there all the time, our squadron.
And the Army moved into Khe Sanh, and later on Khe Sanh fell.
And so I'm sure that all that was a direct result of the way offensive, or Ted offensive, as such.
What impact did the press have on, in your opinion, the outcome of the war?
or the people back home?
And did you have any contact with the press at all?
Did you ever see any journalists or anything while you were in Vietnam?
There was one time when we had some kind of a large insert, a troop insert that we were involved with, that I heard that there was
a journalist going to make the trip.
But I did not see the man personally, and I don't know whether he conducted interviews with any of our people or not.
If he did, it wasn't known.
He may have interviewed some of the soldiers that were put in or whatever, but I didn't have any contact with him at all.
As far as impact of the press on the Vietnam incident, it's hard to say.
With the news media being this up-to-date and on top of everything the way they are now versus, say, like in World War I, World War II, everybody knows almost before it happens what happens.
And I'm sure it was quite...

disarming to the family and loved ones back home of the men in Vietnam hearing every day that so many had been killed and so many had been wounded and trying to show the score like a football game as to who killed the most that day.
You can't really build morale on that, I don't believe.
Do you think that was an effective way of telling how the war was going, who killed the most?
Was that an effective measure?
No.
It's hard to say what would have been an effective measure for Vietnam.
The way it actually turned out, nobody won and everybody lost.
I'm sure there would have been different ways for things to have been handled.
I don't know what.
I mean, who can second guess politicians and everything?

Politicians have always cracked my ass anyway in the fact that they're more concerned about their Democratic Party or their Republican Party than they are about the American people and the American nation as a whole.
to do anything for a damn vote.
Do you think the politicians had an effect?
What kind of effect do you think they had on the outcome of the war?
Well, I think they loused it up.
It was a loused-up situation to begin with.
But as far as...
I don't know.
Public opinion had a lot to do with...

with the outcome of the war, if everybody had not been afraid of making a decision, be it right or wrong, and going ahead and made a decision somewhere earlier in the game, I think it could have been ended a lot sooner and to our benefit.
But everyone was afraid of what the other guy was going to think about it.
It was a waste, a total waste.
I'm proud to have served for my country, and I did what little part I did, but it was a farce and injustice.
You referred to before, first you said the Vietnam War, and then you change it to rather the conflict.
You seem to be reluctant to call it a war.
Is that because we didn't declare war?
Right.
Nobody wants to call it a war.
They were afraid to declare war.
It's sort of related to the Korean incident or conflict or whatever.
It takes an act of Congress to declare war, but then again they can send all the young men of the country over to sacrifice their life and limbs.
and think they can get by without calling it a war.
But if they had gone ahead and declared war, I think we could have won it.
Do you think we should have, LBJ should have called in the reserves?
I don't think the reserves would have had any effect on it.
He had plenty of resources to use without the reserves if he would have just used the right resources.
Okay.
Do you have any opinion about a certain way we should have gone about it in order to win the war?
How could we have won?
Any particular way?
You might have done things differently.
No, no real strategies or anything like that.
I'm not a strategist or the like, but just needed to go in and kick ass and get it over with.
Like I say, they had all the technology and the firepower and the manpower to do something about it, but they'd take one step forward and two steps back, and you can't win by doing like that.
What kind of feelings or what kind of welcome did you have when you went back home as far as the anti-war movement?
Was it going on at the time?
How were the veterans treated?
when they returned?
Well, I come from a small town.
And everybody pretty well knows everybody.
Of course, my family welcomed me back with open arms.
But I'd walk down the street, and the general people would act like, well, you've been gone away for a while.
What you been doing?
And I'd say, well, I just got back from Vietnam.
Oh, really?
You know, big deal.
They really didn't give a damn if I was in Vietnam or next door or what.
There was no real antagonism towards me or where I'd been or what I'd done, but there was no moral support in saying, boy, I'm sure glad you're back.
I'm sure glad you went over and did your job and all that.
people didn't seem to give a damn.
As far as anti-war movement was concerned, I didn't really notice any.
Anytime you have anything like that, you're going to have some, but the major portion came later on, like with Kent State and the like.
At the time that I was in, it was very negligible.
But it really did right my ass that people just didn't really give a damn.
You think the vets were looked down upon for maybe what the American people saw on TV?
Did they blame y'all?
Did you get any of those kind of feelings?
I didn't personally.
Like I say, I'm from a small town, and things like that don't get developed quite as much.
But there were a number of vets that did get frowned upon, evidently, according to the media and the like later on.

But I think a lot of that's brought on by the vets in the fact that, like I was mentioning earlier, they think the United States and society owes them for what they did, which I totally disagree with.
Okay, how much of a disruption did the war have on your family relationship as far as not seeing your daughter until nine months after she was born with your wife?
What kind of effect did that have on you?
There was more of an effect between me and my daughter than...
my wife and I.

There was no problem between my wife and I. I think there was a little bit of, and probably still is, a little bit of a problem between my daughter and I, even though it's hard to put your finger on it.
I came back from Vietnam.
She was nine months old.
I didn't get to go through the
latter stages of pregnancy or the birth, the first few weeks and the first few months with her just becoming a person.
And when I got home, she was a nine-month, what can you say, crying machine.
And it got to me at times.
I hate to say it, but I'm sure somewhere along the line I've sort of maybe held that against her a little bit.
Who did you hold it against?
Well, I held it, I guess, against my daughter in the fact that here I was coming back from Vietnam wanting some
peace and tranquility in my life.
And she was there to, I guess you might say, come between my wife and I.
And I hope I haven't harmed her.
I've tried to make up for it.
But then again, I believe
Somewhere in there, there's got to be some repercussion of my coming back showing, and I'm sure I did, show some animosity towards him.
Do you have any particular bitterness towards any politician, a president maybe, or any other person to this day as a result of the war?
Do you carry any bitterness with you?
Well, there's a certain degree of bitterness, I would say, but I can't really pinpoint it on any person or administration.
Something like that was an error on everyone's part.
And in order to say that any one person or
the like is at fault would be an injustice on my part because I'm in no position to say
